{# ================================================================
   §12 CYBER INCIDENT DECISION TOOL (CIDT)
   ================================================================ #}
<h2><span class="sec-num">12</span> Cyber Incident Decision Tool (CIDT)</h2>
<div class="info-box">
<p>The <strong>Cyber Incident Decision Tool (CIDT)</strong> is Aajimatics' proprietary decision-support framework that helps organisations respond effectively when a cyber incident occurs. It provides a structured, step-by-step response playbook tailored to your organisation's sector, regulatory environment, and the type of incident detected.</p>
<p>CIDT integrates directly with this CIDA assessment, using your risk profile and findings to pre-configure response priorities. Access the CIDT through the Aajimatics SaaS platform.</p>
</div>

<div class="page-break"></div>

{# ================================================================
   §13 WHAT IS CYBER INSURANCE?
   ================================================================ #}
<h2><span class="sec-num">13</span> What is Cyber Insurance?</h2>
<p>Cyber insurance is a specialist insurance product that provides financial protection against the costs arising from cyber incidents, including data breaches, ransomware attacks, business interruption, and regulatory penalties. It complements — but does not replace — an organisation's own cyber security controls.</p>

<div class="coverage-grid">
  <div class="coverage-card">
    <h4>First-Party Coverage</h4>
    <p class="small">Costs incurred directly by the insured organisation:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Ransomware extortion payments and negotiation</li>
      <li>Business interruption and revenue loss</li>
      <li>Forensic investigation and incident response</li>
      <li>Data recovery and system restoration</li>
      <li>PR and crisis communications</li>
      <li>Funds transfer fraud (system-based)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="coverage-card">
    <h4>Third-Party Coverage</h4>
    <p class="small">Costs arising from claims by third parties:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Privacy liability — data breach notification costs</li>
      <li>Civil claims from affected individuals or partners</li>
      <li>Regulatory fines (NDPR, GDPR, PCI-DSS)</li>
      <li>Network security liability — passing malware to others</li>
      <li>Media liability — defamation via digital channels</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

{# ================================================================
   §14 FAQs
   ================================================================ #}
<h2><span class="sec-num">14</span> Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq-item avoid-break">
  <div class="faq-q">How are the risk scores calculated?</div>
  <div class="faq-a">CIDA uses a blended model combining questionnaire responses (weighted by control importance), technical findings (severity-weighted with CVE enrichment), and actuarial priors derived from 20+ industry sources including IBM, DBIR, Coalition, and ENISA. The model is calibrated for African market conditions.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item avoid-break">
  <div class="faq-q">What does "Annual Probability" mean in §3?</div>
  <div class="faq-a">This is the estimated probability that an incident of the stated type will occur at least once within the next 12 months, given your organisation's current risk profile. It is derived from a Poisson frequency model blended with your specific threat vector scores.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item avoid-break">
  <div class="faq-q">How should we prioritise the remediation items?</div>
  <div class="faq-a">Prioritise by the combination of risk score uplift (higher = more impact on your overall posture) and implementation effort. Items marked Critical should be addressed within 30 days; High within 90 days; Medium within 6 months.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item avoid-break">
  <div class="faq-q">Will fixing these issues automatically lower our insurance premium?</div>
  <div class="faq-a">Demonstrating remediation of the Conditions listed in the underwriting recommendation can lead to a re-assessment and potential premium reduction. Contact Aajimatics to schedule a re-assessment after significant remediation work is completed.</div>
</div>

<div class="faq-item avoid-break">
  <div class="faq-q">Is this report shared with insurance underwriters?</div>
  <div class="faq-a">With your consent, a summarised technical scorecard (not the full report) is shared with the issuing underwriter to support policy issuance. The full report remains confidential to your organisation.</div>
</div>

<div class="page-break"></div>

{# ================================================================
   §15 GLOSSARY
   ================================================================ #}
<h2><span class="sec-num">15</span> Glossary</h2>
{% set glossary = [
  ("CIDA", "Cyber Intelligence Decision Algorithm — Aajimatics' AI-powered cyber risk scoring engine."),
  ("CVE", "Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures — a standardised identifier for publicly known security vulnerabilities."),
  ("CVSS", "Common Vulnerability Scoring System — a numeric score (0-10) indicating a vulnerability's severity."),
  ("CWE", "Common Weakness Enumeration — a categorisation of software security weaknesses."),
  ("DMARC", "Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting and Conformance — an email authentication protocol that prevents domain spoofing."),
  ("EPSS", "Exploit Prediction Scoring System — a probability score estimating the likelihood a CVE will be exploited in the wild."),
  ("KEV", "Known Exploited Vulnerabilities — CISA's catalogue of CVEs actively exploited by threat actors."),
  ("NDPR / NDPA", "Nigeria Data Protection Regulation / Act — Nigeria's primary data protection legislation."),
  ("OWASP", "Open Web Application Security Project — a non-profit producing free, open resources on web application security."),
  ("Penetration Test", "An authorised simulated cyber attack against a computer system, conducted to identify security weaknesses."),
  ("Ransomware", "Malware that encrypts a victim's data and demands payment (ransom) for the decryption key."),
  ("SPF", "Sender Policy Framework — an email authentication method that prevents email spoofing by verifying the sender's IP address."),
  ("Threat Vector", "A pathway or means by which an attacker can gain access to a computer or network in order to deliver a payload."),
  ("Zero-Day", "A vulnerability that is unknown to those responsible for patching it — often exploited before a fix is available."),
] %}
{% for term, defn in glossary %}
<div class="avoid-break">
  <div class="gloss-term">{{ term }}</div>
  <div class="gloss-def">{{ defn }}</div>
</div>
{% endfor %}

<div class="page-break"></div>

